<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/books-arts <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/books-arts" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 25 日星期二 18:07:48 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[A Soap Maker Cracks the Code to ‘Made in America’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Bath &amp; Body Works 说服供应商在其总部附近的俄亥俄州城市建立生产基地<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822326/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="标签制造商 CCL 是俄亥俄州新奥尔巴尼 Bath &amp; Body Works 的供应商之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>标签制造商 CCL 是俄亥俄州新奥尔巴尼 Bath &amp; Body Works 的供应商之一。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075938"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/austen-hufford" itemprop="url" rel="author">Austen Hufford</a></span> / 摄影：Maddie McGarvey 为《华尔街日报》拍摄</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>俄亥俄州新奥尔巴尼——一瓶价值 7.95 美元的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBWI" class="company-name">Bath &amp; Body Works</a>泡沫洗手液过去需要三个月才能组装完成。这些货物必须从中国、加拿大和弗吉尼亚州运送超过 13,000 英里才能到达该公司位于俄亥俄州的配送中心。</p><p> Bath &amp; Body Works 决定需要更快地将新产品推向市场。结果是美国企业界几乎没有类似的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-companies-on-pace-to-bring-home-record-number-of-overseas-jobs-11660968061?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">生产</a>计划。</p><p>现在，生产的每一步都在位于哥伦布郊区的公司专用“美容公园”内彼此相距仅数英尺的工厂内进行。一家工厂生产发泡泵和机械装置。另一个制造瓶子本身，第三个制造标签，第四个制造肥皂，填充瓶子，贴上标签并在顶部拧上螺丝。第五个包装它。将一瓶酒送到配送中心的时间缩短为 21 天和几英里。 Bath &amp; Body Works 在自营商店销售的大部分产品都是现场制作的。</p><p>这项工作始于 2008 年，需要与有时持怀疑态度的供应商进行大量谈判。该园区包括 10 家制造商和数百万平方英尺的生产和仓库空间，生产高峰期间有 5,000 名员工在那里工作。 Bath &amp; Body Works 去年的销售额为 75.6 亿美元，自 2019 年以来年收入增长超过 20 亿美元。</p><p> “我将 BBW 视为交响乐的作曲家和指挥家，”Bath &amp; Body Works 供应链主管 Susanna Zhu 说道。</p><p>让生产离家更近已成为许多公司的首要任务。 Covid-19、恶劣天气、贸易战、地缘政治紧张局势和船只滞留造成的干扰使消费者无法获得他们想要的沙发和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-is-the-supply-chain-still-so-snarled-we-explain-with-a-hot-tub-11629987531?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">热水浴缸</a>。拜登政府正在斥资数千亿美元，旨在增强电动汽车、电池和半导体等战略性行业的国内影响力。</p><p>政府的资金，加上不断增长的消费者需求和持续存在的供应链问题，正在引发<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-manufacturing-factory-jobs-comeback-3ce0c52c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">工厂建设热潮</a>，支出达到至少 20 年来的最高水平。政府估计，未来十年，公共和私人投资将达到 3.5 万亿美元。</p><p>事实证明，Bath &amp; Body Works 的举措在疫情期间特别有帮助。当竞争对手苦苦应对短缺问题时，BBW 的现场供应商共享原材料甚至员工，以生产更多洗手液和其他急需商品。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822324?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼尔·赖斯 (Daniel Rice) 是 CCL 的印刷机操作员，负责这条生产线的工作。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>首席执行官吉娜·博斯韦尔</p>表示，将企业高管安置在距主要制造商仅一小段车程的地方，可以解决问题并快速开发新产品。<p></p><p> “这太神奇了，尤其是当你需要速度和敏捷性时，”她说。</p><p>该公司与许多零售商一样受益于疫情期间消费者支出的增加，该公司表示今年的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-financial-chief-wendy-arlin-to-leave-e6b40c91?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">销售额可能会下降</a>。</p><p>复制 BBW 模式的一项<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">挑战</a>是，工厂并不是在泡沫中运营，而是依赖于供应商、零部件和专业知识的网络，而转移这些网络的成本高昂。一旦建立了这样的网络，它往往就会陷入困境。</p><p>美国的土地、劳动力以及遵守环境和分区法的成本通常也高于中国和发展中国家。</p><p>适用于肥皂和 BBW 生产的其他两打产品的产品不一定适用于智能手机、搅拌机，甚至是深深扎根于亚洲的高度专业化供应链的背包。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822322?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hari Poudel 在新奥尔巴尼的另一家供应商 KDC/One 包装 Bath &amp; Body Works 肥皂。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>半导体制造商和原钢生产商需要大量的前期投资和规模经济。 BBW 模型更适合利用范围经济，即制造商生产多种产品。 Bath &amp; Body Works 每年可推出约 7,000 种新香味产品。</p><p> BBW 的总部距离美容公园约 10 英里，由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/leslie-wexner-to-leave-board-of-l-brands-11616072589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Les Wexner</a>创立，隶属于其零售集团 L Brands。身体产品销售店从 1990 年的 27 家店增加到 1999 年的 1,000 多家，截至 4 月份已达到 1,810 家。 2021 年，L Brands 剥离了其</p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VSCO" class="company-name">维多利亚的秘密 (Victoria&#39;s Secret)</a>内衣店并更名为 Bath &amp; Body Works，专门专注于该品牌。<p></p><p>该公司选择了新奥尔巴尼作为其美容园区，这是一个靠近主要高速公路的规划社区，距离全国近一半人口仅一天车程。</p><p>新奥尔巴尼希望实现白领经济多元化。为了吸引 BBW，该市创建了分区并安装了基础设施，自身花费 600 万美元，州政府花费 300 万美元。早期工厂于 2011 年在这片占地 450 英亩的土地上开业。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/818b84a5-1525-40bd-9eac-752c4fe195f1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>为了实现这一目标，BBW 必须说服其最好的供应商搬迁。对于供应商来说，好处是继续与快速增长的护肤品销售商开展业务，并获得 BBW 在一定年限内的销量保证。缺点：花费数百万美元搬迁生产并购买新设备。</p><p>生产肥皂瓶分配泵的 Rieke Packaging 不知道是否值得投资。当时，Rieke 在中国的工厂生产该泵。 Rieke 在印第安纳州几个小时路程外有一家现有工厂，有可能为该公园供货，但 Bath &amp; Body Works 表示希望在现场建工厂。</p><p> “从供应商的角度来看，存在很大的阻力，”当时在 Rieke 工作、现在在一家制药公司从事供应链和制造工作的克雷格·米勒 (Craig Miller) 说。 “你希望我们购买更多设备。我们的租赁率将是印第安纳州农村地区的两倍。得了吧，这听起来一点也不好玩。”</p><p>里克决定在新奥尔巴尼投资数百万美元。 “这是一个不容错过的机会，”米勒说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822319?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Corwin Strong 在新奥尔巴尼的 Rieke 从事质量控制工作。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>将生产转移到俄亥俄州并不容易。工厂必须应对规划官员、高昂的劳动力和建筑成本，甚至濒临灭绝的蝙蝠。</p><p> Jeff Stouffer 曾在 Bath &amp; Body Works 负责新产品发布工作，后来加入了一家生产香水和灌装瓶的供应商，该供应商于 2015 年左右在园区开设了一家新工厂。他和其他高管与城市和商业园区官员会面了十几次，讨论相对较小的工厂的美学问题，从墙壁的颜色到公司标志的尺寸等各个方面都进行了谈判。他说，这就像一个服用类固醇的房主协会。</p><p> “他们对它的外观非常严格，”他说。</p><p>由于可能存在一种濒临灭绝的蝙蝠，因此无法砍伐现场的树木，导致施工推迟了几个月。</p><p>尽管如此，几乎每家公司的扩张都超出了最初的投资。</p><p> “从现在起 5 到 10 年后的支出将需要 2 到 3 年的时间来实现，”斯托弗说。</p><p>降低成本是最大的挑战。</p><p>并非所有生产步骤一开始都是在俄亥俄州进行的。 Rieke 最初在新奥尔巴尼模制了两个外部塑料部件，可以由多种颜色制成。然后它将它们连接到仍然是中国制造的泵的内核上。</p><p>曾在 Rieke 工作、现担任咨询工程师的工程师 Will Nguyen 表示，2020 年左右，Bath &amp; Body Works 表示，它确实希望在美国生产整个泡沫肥皂泵，而且 BBW 也不想支付超过每件约 20 至 25 美分的价格。</p><p>双方商定了一项多年供应商协议，将泵发动机的生产从中国带到校园。阮说，几个月来，我们并不清楚这种情况是否会发生。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822332?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> KDC/One 提供一瓶 Bath &amp; Body Works 肥皂。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Nguyen 表示，Rieke 同意在俄亥俄州以基本相同的单位成本制造整个泵，Bath &amp; Body Works 帮助 Rieke 获得批量保证以及与其他公司的全球采购和供应商协议。</p><p>现在，里克必须弄清楚如何在俄亥俄州制造水泵并实现盈利。他们转向自动化。</p><p>在中国，制造由 13 部分组成的泵是一个手工过程，需要大量工人处理微小的弹簧和球。 Rieke 的母公司 TriMas Packaging 的高管马克·博克斯 (Mark Box) 表示：“我们无法复制在俄亥俄州中部海外进行的手动流程，但让机器来复制这项工作却很复杂。” “你的零件非常小，移动速度非常快。最轻微的事情都可能导致堵塞。”</p><p>机器必须使泵足够紧以将液体保留在内部，但又不能太紧以致无法运行。这些机器还必须处理塑料和其他原材料在运输过程中的差异。</p><p> Nguyen 估计，美国的生产需要大约 10 名员工，需要 1200 万美元的资本投资，而中国类似的生产能力需要大约 50 名员工，投资不到 200 万美元。</p><p>自动化和邻近性意味着泵及其零件可以在不到一个月的时间内到达并完全制造出来，而之前是五个月。 Rieke 每年向 Bath &amp; Body Works 销售约 3 亿个泵。</p><p>新奥尔巴尼认为美容园区可以成为其他公司和社区的典范。它吸引了一家<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMGN" class="company-name">安进</a>制药厂。去年，英特尔选择新奥尔巴尼作为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-to-invest-at-least-20-billion-in-ohio-chip-making-facility-11642750760?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">价值 200 亿美元的半导体工厂</a>的所在地。该公司表示，英特尔工厂将吸引数十家新的本地供应商，包括半导体设备制造商和其他材料供应商。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822327?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在新奥尔巴尼的 Axium，人们正在制作 Bath &amp; Body Works 瓶子的模具。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该园区的成功及其在旺季期间的数千名员工意味着一些位置较近的制造商担心劳动力短缺。 Bath &amp; Body Works 最近允许一些供应商在俄亥俄州其他地区开设工厂以吸引新工人。</p><p> BBW 如今的战略围绕其美容园的独特特性：快速交付新产品。 Bath &amp; Body Works 定期推出新鲜香气，并注重快速设计和生产。这种模式使 BBW 能够收取高价，避免折扣和剩菜，并有助于弥补本地制造的额外成本。</p><p>本月早些时候推出的 Wild Sand 香氛（香调：仙人掌果、仙人掌花和温暖的龙舌兰花蜜）有洗手液、蜡烛、沐浴露、香水、消毒喷雾、润肤露和美黑剂可供选择。</p><p>与大多数提前几个月预订当季所有产品的零售商不同，Bath &amp; Body Works 的目标是预订大约三分之二的产品。然后，它会密切监控销售情况，并为获胜产品下额外的“即时”订单。</p><p> “实际上，一周之内，这些产品就发货了，”肥皂制造商和填充剂 KDC/One 的首席执行官尼古拉斯·惠特利 (Nicholas Whitley) 说。</p><p>位于同一地点意味着制造商可以使用校园运输服务轻松地将样品发送到流程的下一阶段或发送给 Bath &amp; Body Works 主管进行签字，无需隔夜运输。商店里的东西的气味、感觉或外观很难通过 Zoom 通话传达。</p><p> “有些闪光、全息图无法翻译，”标签制造商 CCL Label 的图形经理 Tom DeCicco 说。 “你在照片中看不到这一点。”</p><p>写信给奥斯汀·赫福德： <a href="mailto:austen.hufford@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">austen.hufford@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0<author><![CDATA[Austen Hufford]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>华尔街日报华盛顿</category><category>零售批发</category><category>化妆品/香水零售</category><category>服装零售</category><category>专业零售</category><category>零售</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>供应链</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>沐浴及美体工程</category><category>BBWI</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>供应链</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>化妆品</category><category>香水零售</category><category>服装零售</category><category>专业零售</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Look’ Review: Life as It Is, Blinkers Removed]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>集中注意力不仅仅是集中注意力或集中注意力；它可能意味着进入高度意识的状态，就像捕猎的掠食者一样。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590096382887103008"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822898?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Shutterstock / Juriah Mosin </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590096382887103008"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/meghan-cox-gurdon" itemprop="url" rel="author">梅根·考克斯·格登</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 6:11 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/look-review-life-as-it-is-blinkers-removed-794e456"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>年轻时，克里斯蒂安·马兹比约 (Christian Madsbjerg) 在图书馆里闲逛时，发现了亚里士多德的一段话，觉得很荒谬。亚里士多德在《物理学》中解释说，物体向地球下落是因为它们想回到它们所属的地方。当马兹比约先生重读这些台词时，他感到自己的嘲笑变成了头晕。 “在（亚里士多德）的世界里，物体掉落在地上是因为它们想家了，”马兹比约先生在《看》一书中写道，这是一部具有挑衅性、有时难以捉摸的探究和指导著作。两千年前的一位哲学家对引力一无所知，这本身并不令人惊讶。令马兹比约先生感动的是他意识到亚里士多德一定真的相信他所写的内容。</p><p>这位出生于丹麦的企业家写道：“从那以后，我多次遇到了那种融合洞察力的眩晕感。”他的职业生涯建立在追求感知突破的基础上。在《Look》中，马兹比约先生试图传授他从艺术和哲学中获得的智慧，以及从经营一家企业咨询公司和在纽约新学院教授“人类观察”课程的实践经验中获得的智慧。他的书中充满了有趣的好东西：源自广泛来源的轶事和戒律，以及格式塔理论家和现象学实践者的工作总结，他将现象学定义为“研究人类世界如何运作以及赋予我们生命意义的一切事物”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><p><strong>看看：如何在分心的世界中集中注意力</strong></p><p><em>克里斯蒂安·马兹比约</em></p><p><em>（Riverhead，234 页，29 美元）</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/9618f397-9a69-46f1-b501-13c5d8046de9.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>这个定义的广度和模糊性表明了这本书的热情过度。这里有很多东西，而且很多都是有道理的，但有时争论是如此分散，以至于让人感觉不稳定。有时，马兹比约先生徘徊在平庸甚至语无伦次的边缘。但他从不翻倒，因为他所说的毫无疑问是真实的。而且，公平地说，表面理解和深刻理解之间的区别很难区分。甚至很难描述。马兹比约先生在寻求捕捉突然顿悟的体验方面做出了一项英勇的工作。</p><p>他认为，“最丰富的现实”不是通过思考而是通过观察来实现的——他的意思是广泛使用一个人的感知装置。这句话听起来很容易遵循，但事实并非如此。寻找需要时间。观看需要让喋喋不休的头脑安静下来。观察不仅意味着让眼睛追随闪亮的弹跳物体，还意味着要吸收物体周围的广阔环境，并注意哪些不闪亮、不弹跳。也许最具挑战性的是，这意味着放弃我们必然看到我们认为我们看到的东西的想法。因为，正如 Madsbjerg 先生所解释的那样，“感知发生在我们内心；感知发生在我们内心；感知发生在我们的内心。”我们改变我们所看到的，以反映我们在世界上的身份和位置。”</p><p>用格特鲁德·斯坦因的话来说，玫瑰可能就是玫瑰，但对于植物学家、室内设计师或热恋中的追求者来说，玫瑰有着截然不同的含义。当我们瞥见一朵玫瑰或任何其他东西时，我们会看到它所蕴含的含义。这就是格式塔的概念，即事物可识别的“完整性”。再举个例子，我们很少有人会停下来评估一张餐桌和一组椅子的颜色、大小、形状和构成，然后再对它们的性质和用途得出结论。野餐午餐、博物馆画廊或拥挤的公交车站的格式塔也是如此：很容易在不注意任何细节的情况下记录一个场景。</p><p>这种快速理解我们所看到的事物的能力使我们能够继续日常生活，但它也可能成为清晰度的障碍，让我们戴上眼罩并导致我们错过重要的信号。 《看》充满了人们的故事，他们努力只见树木、见树，或者只见森林，而不是其他地方。有一则轶事讲述了一家电子公司的一位高管，他如此专注于开发复杂的大屏幕电视，以至于错过了通过笔记本电脑和智能手机观看电视的文化转变。另一篇报道讲述了出生于城市的传记作家罗伯特·卡罗如何不得不在得克萨斯州乡村的开阔滑雪隔离中度过很长时间，然后他才觉得自己可以开始理解他的主题林登·约翰逊。</p><p>马兹比约先生在波罗的海的一个丹麦岛屿上的马克思主义环境中长大，他亲身体会到，从意识形态的角度看问题也可能令人眼花缭乱。 “对于青少年来说，共产主义是一种全面的、充满活力的、愤怒的信仰，”他写道。 “我对世界上阶级不平等的热情感到欣喜若狂。”只有当他的革命热情消退时，他才能看到意识形态如何扭曲了他的世界观。在他的讲述中，柏林墙的倒塌成为了开始探索思维时尚如何前进和后退的动力。为什么人们会改变主意；以及是否有可能预测社会变革，“感受到风暴即将来临的迹象”。</p><p>那么，对于想要“在分心的世界中集中注意力”的读者来说，该如何进行呢？看来，第一步是要了解注意力可以有多种形式。注意力并不像我们想象的那样仅仅是集中注意力或全神贯注；而是集中注意力。它可能意味着进入其他高度警觉的状态，例如捕食者在狩猎时的多维警惕性或“注意力的目光”——普遍的警觉性或灵活的准备状态，例如运动场上的运动员或快速行驶的交通中的司机。</p><p>当我们的感官活跃并处于接受状态时，我们可能会发现更容易注意到预示着即将发生转变的趋势、异常或雄辩的社会沉默。这些技能当然在工作中有用，在家里也有用。 “对于我们任何人来说，未来从来都不是一个理论上的前景。你可以在日常生活中观察到它，”Madsbjerg 先生承诺道。 “对我们所有人来说，最具挑战性的事情就是看到真实存在的东西。”</p><p><em>格登夫人是《杂志》的撰稿人，也是《魔法时刻：分心时代大声朗读的神奇力量》一书的作者。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 22:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/look-review-life-as-it-is-blinkers-removed-794e456</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/look-review-life-as-it-is-blinkers-removed-794e456<author><![CDATA[Meghan Cox Gurdon]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘I Am Not There Anymore’ by the Clientele Review: Love, Loss and Indie Rock]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这支伦敦乐队的第七张专辑充满了活泼、旋律优美的歌曲创作，让人想起披头士乐队和多诺万等经典乐队，同时对死亡进行了思考。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590107990873967622"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822571?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">客户群</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安迪·威尔舍尔</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590107990873967622"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马克·理查森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 5:55 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-am-not-there-anymore-by-the-clientele-review-love-loss-and-indie-rock-ecd80d58"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>当一个人第一次遇到客户时，这有点像被告知一个共同的秘密。在美国，伦敦独立摇滚乐队自 2000 年代初以来就以 Merge 厂牌发行音乐，并取得了一定的成功——巡演广受好评，专辑登上了出版物的年终榜单。但《客户》一直都是一种邪教行为，深受其奉献者的喜爱，但大多不为更广泛的音乐界所知。该乐队由主唱兼吉他手阿拉斯代尔·麦克莱恩 (Alasdair MacLean) 领导，他们创作的吉他音乐充满了 60 年代的经典吉他流行音乐和 80 年代和 90 年代的英国独立音乐，其歌曲旋律丰富，总是充满了引人注目的抒情意象。但 Clientele 似乎注定是一支在当时几乎不为人所知的乐队，但后来却被后代兴奋地发现。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822534?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p>考虑到该组织不稳定的商业地位，它长期不活跃并且经常处于永久解散的边缘是可以理解的。在经历了 2000 年代忙碌而富有成效的时期后，客户发行了出色的单曲合辑《Suburban Light》（2000 年）以及包括《Strange Geometry》（2005 年）和《God Save the Clientele》（2007 年）在内的优秀唱片，而 Clientele 已经八年没有发行完整唱片了，自 2017 年最新的《Music for the Age of Miracles》以来，已经有六年了。如果他们在那里结束事情，那就不足为奇了。但该乐队的第七张专辑“I Am Not There Anymore”（合并）将于周五发行。更令人意想不到的是，它是客户最奇怪的产品之一，也是最好的产品之一。</p><p>这张唱片以令人愉快的八分钟漫无目的曲目“Silverlink 的寓言”开始，它作为一种序曲，用随后在 LP 中再次出现的语言介绍了专辑的主题和图像。这张专辑的灵感部分来自于麦克莱恩先生对 1997 年母亲去世的回忆，而开场曲目中的“她在五月即将死去”就是其中的众多参考之一（另一首曲目也将这句话的一部分作为标题）。虽然歌词阴暗而沉重，但《银链寓言》的音乐基调通常是轻松活泼的，其中一个部分有有效的波萨诺瓦插曲，迷人的大提琴线条贯穿整首歌曲。</p><p> 《我不再在那里》是一部最值得欣赏的作品。这是一张相对较长的专辑——19首曲目，63分钟——其中适当的歌曲与乐器插曲缝合在一起，将听众从一个场景带到下一个场景。第二首歌“Radial B”就是这样的插曲。它的长度不到一分钟，由几个长长的钢琴音符组成，结束后，民谣“Garden Eye Mantra”用带有鼻音的吉他和精心设计的弦乐编排来接续主线。麦克莱恩先生唱道：“黑暗中，掀背车在滚动/车窗打开，香烟在发光。”这句引人注目的对句强调了他在你脑海中留下画面的能力。</p><p>这张唱片似乎徘徊在清醒生活和梦境之间，而记忆是一个常见的试金石。在麦克莱恩先生的世界里，生活的时刻似乎不像幻想那样真实，他的人物不断地在遐想中进进出出。在《Blue Over Blue》这首歌中，麦克莱恩先生用弹拨的原声吉他、模糊的贝斯和闪闪发光的圆号部分演唱了“玩捉迷藏/在门之间/度过毁灭的一年”。</p><p>客户通过创作不可磨灭的旋律来创造实验的自由度。麦克莱恩先生钦佩经典的音乐大师——披头士乐队、僵尸乐队、多诺万——他们被期望能演奏出让你从第一部剧中就着迷的歌曲。因此，尽管他的歌词和概念可能晦涩难懂，但人们仍然会发现很多可以哼唱的内容，以及可爱的器乐副歌——从齐声、Byrdsian 到令人着迷的弦乐编曲，可以与数十年来最好的吉他流行音乐相媲美。这种音乐技巧贯穿于《I Am Not There Anymore》中，即使器乐部分转向抽象或尖锐的不和谐音。 “Chalk Flowers”中的歌词让人想起披头士乐队“Norwegian Wood”的总体形状，而“Lady Grey”则让人想起海龟乐队轻松阳光的流行音乐。</p><p>但这些歌曲表面光明，内心阴暗。 《我不再在那里》讲述的是时间的稳步前进所揭示的始终存在的死亡现实。白天变成夜晚，季节更替，这些变化的每一个细节似乎都融入到了麦克莱恩先生的一首歌词中。对他来说，生活充满了如此多的奇迹和神秘，很难相信它会发生。 “我知道那天晚上我会睡觉/管子会向我唱歌/但我不太相信/我在那里，”他在唱片后期的“Through the Roses”中说道。以如此亲密和深思熟虑的主题来建立成功的音乐事业并不容易。但对于那些认同麦克莱恩先生世界观的人来说，没有任何一支乐队能像这支乐队那样传递出美丽的存在主义思考。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。理查森是《华尔街日报》的摇滚和流行音乐评论家。在 Twitter 上关注他@MarkRichardson。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-am-not-there-anymore-by-the-clientele-review-love-loss-and-indie-rock-ecd80d58</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-am-not-there-anymore-by-the-clientele-review-love-loss-and-indie-rock-ecd80d58<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Poliuto,’ ‘Crispino e la Comare’ and ‘Henri VIII’ Reviews: Overlooked Operas, Revisited]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在林肯中心，新剧院上演了两部美声作品，一部是多尼采蒂的作品，以基督教殉道者为主题，另一部是仙女教母费德里科和路易吉·里奇的作品；在北部，巴德·夏景 (Bard SummerScape) 制作的卡米尔·圣桑 (Camille Saint-Saëns) 历史剧展现了国王的暴政。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590107991197678032"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822619?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">里卡多·何塞·里维拉和切尔西·莱内亚</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：史蒂文·皮萨诺/Teatro Nuovo </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590107991197678032"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">海蒂·威尔森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 5:52 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/poliuto-crispino-e-la-comare-and-henri-viii-reviews-overlooked-operas-revisited-c7bf20dc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>纽约</em></p><p>如今纽约市夏季几乎没有什么歌剧可看，因此我们更有理由感谢威尔·克拉奇菲尔德 (Will Crutchfield) 富有进取精神的新剧院 (Teatro Nuovo)，该剧院专门表演历史悠久的美声唱法作品。本季带来了两部稀有作品：盖塔诺·多尼采蒂 (Gaetano Donizetti) 的悲剧《波利乌托》(Poliuto) 和上周在林肯中心玫瑰剧院 (Lincoln Center&#39;s Rose Theatre) 上演的喜剧片《克里斯皮诺与科马雷》(Crispino e la Comare)，后者由现已被遗忘的兄弟二人组费德里科和路易吉·里奇 (Federico and Luigi Ricci) 创作。两场演出都是半舞台表演，简单地投影历史布景图来营造气氛，而干练的合唱团也为演出做好了准备。</p><p> 《Poliuto》写于 1838 年，但由于审查问题直到 1848 年才上演，这是一部非常棒的作品，充满活力的咏叹调、二重唱和合奏的情节紧凑。萨尔瓦多·卡马拉诺 (Salvatore Cammarano) 的剧本以 259 年的亚美尼亚为背景，讲述了名义上的罗马军官和秘密皈依基督教的人 (圣波利厄克托斯 (St. Polyeuktos)) 的故事；他的妻子宝琳娜；还有罗马总督塞维罗，保琳娜以前的爱人，她相信他已经死了，但现在又出现了。故事情节围绕着嫉妒被信仰战胜的情节展开，波留托最终在保利娜的陪伴下接受了殉道。</p><p>乐谱具有多尼采蒂《露西亚》的轻快节奏和花腔抒情，但也预示着早期威尔第歌剧的戏剧分量。古典乐器管弦乐队位于观众席，而不是在坑里，由雅各布·莱曼（Jakob Lehmann）权威领导——按照古典乐器的做法，他站在乐团前面，偶尔拿起小提琴。除了一开始的一些酸涩的巴松管段落外，乐团的演奏充满了活力和灵活性，单簧管首席玛丽斯·莱戈特(Maryse Legault)在引入女高音的令人惊叹的独奏时刻中大放异彩。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822620?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">圣地亚哥·巴莱里尼</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：史蒂文·皮萨诺/Teatro Nuovo</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>训练有素的主唱为他们的角色带来了连奏的优雅和戏剧性的强度。男高音圣地亚哥·巴莱里尼（Santiago Ballerini）是一位出色的波利乌托（Poliuto），他以时尚的方式平衡了他的愤怒爆发和他对神圣的暗示，尤其是在他的第二幕咏叹调中。切尔西·雷内亚 (Chelsea Lehnea) 饰演的保琳娜 (Paolina) 展现了一位强有力的、听起来略显僵硬的女高音，以及精准的花腔和令人印象深刻的动态控制。宝琳娜（Paolina）扮演玛丽亚·卡拉斯（Maria Callas）的角色，而莱内亚女士有时似乎过度引导了这位女主角的过度热情。作为塞韦罗，里卡多·何塞·里维拉（Ricardo José Rivera）在被要求扮演沉重的角色而不是失望的情人时，他那洪亮的男中音表现得最好。汉斯·塔什吉安 (Hans Tashjian) 的低音对于朱庇特大祭司卡利斯汀 (Callistene) 来说显得异常轻盈。</p><p>歌剧中的喜剧总是比悲剧更难，而《克里斯皮诺》（1850）——关于一个贫穷的鞋匠被仙女教母（La Comare）变成医生的故事——是一系列固定的笑话，其中许多都太长，而不是一个完整的夜晚。乔纳森·布兰达尼（Jonathan Brandani）在键盘上大力指挥，男低音男中音马蒂亚·文尼（Mattia Venni）饰演搞笑的克里斯皮诺（Crispino），他出色地表演了快速的意大利语和角色微妙的肢体喜剧。作为克里斯皮诺的妻子，轻浮的安妮塔，特雷莎·卡斯蒂略的高飞花腔对于她的角色长度来说并没有足够的变化——她得到了最重要的独奏时刻，包括最后的回旋曲。有力的女中音莉兹·卡尔佩珀（La Comare）和明亮的男高音托比·布拉德福德（Contino del Fiore）做出了出色的贡献；男低音文森特·格拉纳（米拉波拉诺，一位竞争对手的医生）与维尼先生搭档互相谩骂，成为当晚的亮点。</p><h4> ***</h4><p><em>纽约州哈德逊河畔安嫩代尔</em></p><p>巴德的 SummerScape 音乐节也专注于晦涩难懂的歌剧，今年周五开幕的卡米尔·圣桑的《亨利八世》是一个亮点。该剧于 1883 年为巴黎歌剧院创作，对暴君如何为所欲为进行了精彩的剖析。莱昂斯·德特罗亚特 (Léonce Détroyat) 和保罗-阿曼德·西尔维斯特 (Paul-Armand Silvestre) 创作的剧本虚构了亨利与凯瑟琳·达拉贡 (Catherine d&#39;Aragon) 离婚以及他与安妮·博林 (Anne Boleyn) 结婚的故事，故意表现得不浪漫，导演让·罗曼·韦斯佩里尼 (Jean-Romain Vesperini) 和指挥家莱昂·博特斯坦 (Leon Botstein) 在这个敏锐的舞台表演中巧妙地追踪了其心理操纵。通过一系列冗长的对话场景——表演持续了四个小时，中间有 30 分钟的中场休息——我们追踪每一次对抗的步骤，得出其逻辑结果。其他角色可能认为自己占上风，但亨利总是赢。</p><p>威尔第 16 年前为巴黎歌剧院创作的《唐·卡洛斯》同样以王室权力和宗教斗争为基础。但它突出了爱情和有缺陷的人际关系，而《亨利八世》的关注点则较窄。歌剧中的虚构元素包括一封秘密信件，证明安妮和西班牙驻英国大使唐·戈麦斯·德·费里亚之间早已存在的恋情，以及凯瑟琳和安妮之间的两次戏剧性的相遇，但它们的目的是展示谁在上，谁在下。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多歌剧评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/octavia-e-butlers-parable-of-the-sower-review-lincoln-center-1538641a?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《奥克塔维亚·E·巴特勒的播种者寓言》评论：迷失在歌剧翻译中</a><span class="date">七月 19, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/treemonisha-susannah-and-marcantonio-e-cleopatra-reviews-fatal-love-and-outcasts-arias-36419933?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《Treemonisha》、《Susannah》和《Marc&#39;Antonio e Cleopatra》评论：致命的爱情和弃儿》咏叹调</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 27 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dido-and-aeneas-review-roman-tragedy-in-barcelona-e996c140?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《狄多与埃涅阿斯》评论：巴塞罗那的罗马悲剧</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 20 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/die-zauberflote-review-the-met-humanizes-mozarts-fantasy-c84dabba?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《魔笛》评论：大都会艺术博物馆将莫扎特的幻想人性化</a><span class="date">2023 年 5 月 22 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>《凯瑟琳》由女高音阿曼达·伍德伯里敏感地演唱，有两首凄美的咏叹调——向会议决定亨利是否可以与她离婚的恳求，以及在她濒临死亡时对西班牙祖国的哀悼——这使她成为了这部作品中略带同情心的人物。男低音阿尔弗雷德·沃克 (Alfred Walker) 给亨利带来了沉重的重量和强度，清楚地表明这个故事都是关于他的。中音林赛·阿曼（Mezzo Lindsay Ammann）偶尔刺耳的高音区和引人注目的女低音延伸对​​安妮来说非常有效，她的野心胜过所有其他考虑。乔什·洛弗尔 (Josh Lovell) 纯净的男高音给唐·戈麦斯 (Don Gómez) 披上了纯真的外衣，詹姆斯·巴格韦尔 (James Bagwell) 准备的大型副歌，</p>第三幕的主教会议场景非常精彩，从赞美诗般的庄严转变为喧闹的自由颂歌，支持亨利一举摆脱妻子和罗马的统治。<p></p><p>阿兰·布朗肖 (Alain Blanchot) 设计的都铎王朝服装使这部作品扎根于当时的历史时代；景观设计师 Bruno de Lavenère 和灯光设计师 Christophe Chaupin 使用金属纱布、建筑元素的视频投影和倾斜平台提出了一个更加模糊和阴暗的世界。一个高潮是向主教会议场景的过渡：随着介绍性音乐的展开，光线沿着巨大玫瑰窗的石质窗饰蜿蜒而行，仿佛在现场搭建布景，这是歌剧单手统治的主题的恰当隐喻。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。威尔森为《华尔街日报》撰写歌剧文章，也是《疯狂场景与出口咏叹调：纽约市歌剧院之死与美国歌剧的未来》（大都会出版社）一书的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/poliuto-crispino-e-la-comare-and-henri-viii-reviews-overlooked-operas-revisited-c7bf20dc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/poliuto-crispino-e-la-comare-and-henri-viii-reviews-overlooked-operas-revisited-c7bf20dc<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>歌剧</category><category>剧院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>歌剧</category><category>剧院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[FDIC Scolds Banks for Manipulating Deposit Data]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>银行倒闭后，贷款机构将未投保存款减少了近 2000 亿美元<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080330"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="588" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822609?width=860&amp;height=588" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在《华尔街日报》对 FDIC 文件的分析中，美国银行降低其规定的未保险存款的幅度超过任何其他银行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080330"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jonathan-weil" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔纳森·威尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shane-shifflett" itemprop="url" rel="author">肖恩·希夫莱特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 5:21（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>当硅谷银行陷入财务困境时，其客户纷纷撤离，因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pain-of-silicon-valley-banks-collapse-is-being-felt-by-these-depositors-f18c0bd4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他们的大部分存款都没有投保</a>。几周后，数十家银行调整了数据，减少了他们所说的未投保的存款部分。</p><p>周一，联邦存款保险公司向美国银行发出警告，不要随意调整存款数字。 《华尔街日报》对联邦存款保险公司 (FDIC) 提交的银行文件的分析显示，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BAC" class="company-name">美国银行</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HBAN" class="company-name">亨廷顿国家银行</a>对其未投保存款数量进行了最大的修改。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》分析显示，自 3 月份<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/silicon-valley-bank-svb-financial-what-is-happening-299e9b65?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">硅谷银行倒闭</a>以来，47 家银行重申了 12 月 31 日的未保险存款数字，总计下降了 1,980 亿美元。在硅谷银行，年底 88% 的存款没有保险。</p><p>许多更改其号码的银行试图将一种不寻常的账户类型纳入 FDIC 承保的存款类别中。通常，FDIC 为高达 250,000 美元的存款提供保险。这些账户通常来自政府实体，一般都超过了这个数额，但银行在其背后提供了抵押品，有效地保证了储户在银行倒闭时能够得到偿还。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=13078590-113A-43AC-B5B7-6E1A055FB210&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">当硅谷和 Signature 等银行破产时，联邦存款保险公司正在做它应该做的事情：承保受保存款。以下是 FDIC 的运作方式及其创建原因。图片插图：玛德琳·马歇​​尔<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>FDIC 在给银行的一封信中表示，只有受其保险的存款才能称为保险存款。 FDIC 表示：“抵押品的存在对联邦存款保险所涵盖的存款部分没有影响。”此外，FDIC 表示，一些银行“通过排除子公司的公司间存款余额”错误地显示了较低的数字。 FDIC 拒绝对具体银行发表评论。</p><p>最大的修正来自美国银行。美国银行在 5 月 5 日提交的文件中表示，截至 12 月 31 日，其未保险存款为 7,840 亿美元，比最初报告的金额减少了 1,250 亿美元，即 14%。</p><p>与小型银行不同，美国银行几乎没有受到大规模提款的威胁，因为人们普遍认为政府不会让该银行倒闭。但改变数字可以为美国银行节省数亿美元。</p><p> 5 月份，FDIC 表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-11-2023/card/banks-with-lots-of-uninsured-deposits-would-replenish-fdic-fund-under-new-proposal-Yjsqv5trBsXbXzuTTeCd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将对总资产超过 50 亿美元的银行进行特别评估</a>，以弥补 3 月份硅谷银行和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBNY" class="company-name">Signature 银行</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/signature-bank-is-shut-by-regulators-after-svb-failure-a5f9e0f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">倒闭</a>后为担保未投保存款而花费的 158 亿美元。该评估将基于截至 12 月 31 日银行未投保的存款。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823004?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>根据 FDIC 提出的特别评估公式，使用 12 月 31 日修订后的数字，美国银行在两年内将欠债 19.6 亿美元，低于之前报告的数字 22.7 亿美元。</p><p>美国银行发言人威廉·霍尔丁表示，该行坚持修改后的数字。他表示，该银行已从其无保险存款号码中删除了一些内部或银行内账户，并且不打算再次提交修改。</p><p>第二大修正是由亨廷顿国家银行（Huntington Bancshares 旗下子公司）做出的。亨廷顿在 5 月 26 日提交的文件中表示，截至 12 月 31 日，其未投保存款为 510 亿美元，比之前报告的少 340 亿美元，即 40%。 Huntington, too, would realize significant savings on its special assessment if it were using its revised Dec. 31 number.</p><p> Huntington spokeswoman Tracy Pesho said: “Huntington National Bank restated its uninsured deposit levels to more accurately reflect customer deposits and exclude intercompany cash balances, consistent with other banks and our understanding of the FDIC&#39;s then-current instructions.” She said Huntington is “assessing the statement from the FDIC and determining what the appropriate next steps are.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822610?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> In a late May filing, Huntington National Bank lowered by 40% the amount of uninsured deposits as stated at the end of 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emily Elconin/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In addition to restating uninsured deposits in past reports, other banks changed their definition to reduce them in current reports.</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BOH" class="company-name">Bank of Hawaii</a> in its first-quarter filing with the FDIC showed a 20% drop in uninsured deposits to $8.7 billion, or 42% of total deposits, from $10.8 billion as of the fourth quarter. The main difference was the March 31 deposit number excluded collateralized deposits—a method the FDIC said was unacceptable.<p></p><p> Coincidentally, the bank reported second-quarter earnings Monday. It said its insured and collateralized deposits represented 61% of total deposit balances, up from 58% as of March 31, 2023 and 57% as of June 30, 2022. It didn&#39;t include a figure for uninsured deposits. A Bank of Hawaii spokesman didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> “When you see a small regional bank like Bank of Hawaii that has a sizable amount of deposits that are uninsured, that&#39;s real counterparty risk for the largely corporate depositors that are putting their trust in Bank of Hawaii,” said Brian Pillmore, founder and chief executive officer of Visbanking, which provides data and analysis on US banks.</p><p> Write to Jonathan Weil at <a href="mailto:jonathan.weil@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.weil@wsj.com</a> and Shane Shifflett at <a href="mailto:shane.shifflett@dowjones.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">shane.shifflett@dowjones.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/89390b44-9107-4a43-9db3-d54a5d5e65de.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdic-scolds-banks-for-manipulating-deposit-data-f7fe93d7<author><![CDATA[Jonathan WeilShane Shifflett]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>wsjfinance-rer</category><category> Banking</category><category> Commercial Banking</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>International Banks</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Huntington Bancshares</category><category> HBAN</category><category> Bank of America</category><category> BAC</category><category> Bank of Hawaii</category><category> BOH</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>banking</category><category> commercial banking</category><category> credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>international banks </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hidden Career Cost of Being Overweight]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> New moves to outlaw weight discrimination are pushing companies to examine one of the most insidious forms of on-the-job bias <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074681"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821735?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: WSJ; ISTOCK(3) </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074681"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ray A. Smith</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 24, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Looking back, Michelle Matthews said she often internalized co-workers&#39; comments about her weight. At one work lunch, a teammate remarked on how much she was eating. A higher-up told her she needed to “show up physically as a leader” after she failed to win a promotion.</p><p> It wasn&#39;t until the tech-product design director switched to remote work in 2020 that she grasped how much such slights had colored her office career.</p><p> “I didn&#39;t realize how much I was thinking about my physicality,” said Matthews, 38, who describes herself as a big person. “It took up a lot of my mind.”</p><p> Weight stigma is rarely talked about at work, but it pervades workplaces everywhere, employees and hiring managers say. <a href="https://www.stlouisfed.org/publications/regional-economist/october-2011/worth-your-weight-reexamining-the-link-between-obesity-and-wages#:~:text=Economist%20John%20Cawley%20estimates%20that%20overweight%20and%20obese,percent%20less%2C%20respectively%2C%20than%20normal%20weight%20white%20women." target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Study after study</a> shows heavier people are paid and <a href="https://www.employment-studies.co.uk/system/files/resources/files/526.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">promoted less</a> than thinner colleagues and are often stereotyped as <a href="https://sloanreview.mit.edu/article/the-opportunity-costs-of-weight-bias-at-work/" target="_blank" class="icon none">lazy or undisciplined</a> . In a spring survey of more than 1,000 human-resources executives, 11% said an applicant&#39;s weight had factored into hiring decisions. Half of managers surveyed in a separate poll said they preferred interacting with “healthy-weight” employees, according to SHRM, the human resources professional network that conducted the surveys. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=35CD7B9E-3215-4417-9DEE-8FF9D9BBEDC9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Diabetes drugs could become an effective way to treat behavioral issues and addiction. WSJ&#39;s Daniela Hernandez breaks down the science on how they work and how they could change psychiatry forever. Photo illustration: Elizabeth Smelov<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Now, as New York City and some states move to outlaw weight discrimination at work, companies are beginning to focus on the experience of overweight workers. Many managers are unprepared for the wave of complaints the legislation could bring, advocates for the laws say.</p><p> Weight “is still not looked at from a [diversity and inclusion] perspective,” says Jessica Richman, founder of the Visible Collective, a group that advises companies on supporting workers and consumers who are considered obese.</p><h3> New legal pressure</h3><p> Signed into law in May, the New York City ban adds weight and height to the list of characteristics protected from discrimination, alongside race, gender, age, religion and sexual orientation. Several states, including New Jersey and Massachusetts, have introduced similar bills. (Michigan is currently the only state to prohibit employment discrimination on the basis of weight. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821633?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tech leaders such as Amazon&#39;s Jeff Bezos have been subject to scrutiny over their physiques.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: chandan khanna/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Nearly two-thirds of employers haven&#39;t addressed weight-related stereotyping or bias with their employees, according to SHRM. Though a small number of employers, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">Amazon</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> have formed employee groups to support overweight workers and raise awareness of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/schools-relax-dress-codes-in-bid-to-end-body-shaming-11563010202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“fat-shaming,”</a> they remain the exception.</p><p> Even business leaders who have been vocal advocates of inclusive workplaces say they have given little thought to weight biases until recently.</p><p> “It wasn&#39;t on my radar,” said Jonathan Mildenhall, co-founder and chair of global brand consulting firm TwentyFirstCenturyBrand, who says his company and its corporate clients will have to give the issue more attention. Employers may also need to reconsider workplace <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-your-company-need-to-know-your-body-mass-index-11549902536?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">weight-loss challenges</a> or other programs and benefits, including reimbursement for drugs <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-want-ozempic-for-weight-loss-few-employers-want-to-pay-for-it-215fb5c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">such as Ozempic</a> , he said.</p><h3> Business leaders get buff</h3><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-weight-loss-body-positivity-marketing-6e918f8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">body-positivity movement</a> that championed fat acceptance, plus-size fashion models and extended clothing sizes over the past decade helped fuel the recent weight-discrimination legislation. Now, the rise of Ozempic, Wegovy and similar treatments may lead some people to conclude obesity is a choice if losing weight is a matter of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-housewife-isnt-on-ozempic-how-a-weight-loss-craze-is-shaping-reality-tv-afb21602?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking a drug</a> .</p><p> Pressure to be fit is already intense for anyone aspiring to rise through the management ranks, some executives say. The internet is awash in images and reports of how tech leaders such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/jeff-bezos">Jeff Bezos</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">Mark Zuckerberg</a> achieved their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ceo-workout-abs-bezos-musk-11662166439?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">now-buff physiques</a> . And some leadership coaches say staying trim is virtually <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324595704578241573341483946?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a requirement</a> for getting on the CEO track.</p><p> Keith Wolf, managing partner of recruiting firm Murray Resources in Houston, said he has never heard a corporate client cite a job candidate&#39;s weight for deciding against them. But it would be naive to think appearance isn&#39;t a factor. “You can just kind of look at who actually is hired for certain roles,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822358?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Former IBM Chief Executive Ginni Rometty said in a memoir that she was encouraged to lose weight to get ahead.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alex Kraus/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Companies, he added, are “worried about how leaders are perceived and everything they do, how they dress, how they show up in meetings.”</p><p> In her recent memoir “Good Power,” former <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IBM" class="company-name">IBM</a> Chief Executive Ginni Rometty recounted how, earlier in her career, when she had put on weight, a boss suggested trimming down would help her get ahead.</p><p> Take a look at other high-level executives, and “most seem to be in good physical shape,” he pointed out to her.</p><p></p> Michael Hearn, a 59-year-old information technology program manager, says he has been overweight for much of his career. When he sought informal feedback as to why he was passed over for promotions, “they would say, &#39;Everyone knows you&#39;re a smart guy, everybody knows you work hard. You just don&#39;t present well because of your size,&#39;” he said.<p></p><p> He lost 200 pounds in recent years and has since left his job while he plots a career reset, he said.</p><h3> Remote-work revelations</h3><p> Remote work has transformed daily life for some people who are overweight. Matthews, the tech product design director, said she didn&#39;t worry as much about what to wear or her physical presence once she began working from home in 2020. When on-screen, she could angle the camera in ways that flattered or played down her figure.</p><p> New job opportunities opened up, which she partly attributes to working and interviewing virtually. She landed a role in 2021 as a director of product design at a healthcare company, and later, a promotion to senior director.</p><p> “The course of my career really changed when I went remote,” she said.</p><p> Weight discrimination cases rarely succeed. Some workers have filed suits invoking the Americans with Disabilities Act, which protects job candidates and employees from discrimination, harassment or retaliation because of a disability. Most courts have held that obesity isn&#39;t a disability under the ADA unless it is caused by an underlying health condition. The Texas Supreme Court said as much in a <a href="https://www.txcourts.gov/media/1456743/220179.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">ruling in June</a> , when it decided against a medical resident who alleged she had been fired from Texas Tech University Health Sciences Center because of her obesity.</p><p> Some companies have formed employee groups to raise awareness of fat bias. Amazon&#39;s Body Positive Peers, formed in 2020, often uses its meetings and blog posts to highlight the corrosive effects of fat-shaming and ways to make the company&#39;s products and services more size inclusive.</p><p> JAMS, a global provider of dispute-resolution services, launched a similar employee group two years ago. Its HR chief, Tracy Curry, says its existence helps signal to hires that the company cares about the challenges overweight workers can face.</p><p> Karen Pavlin, chief equity and inclusion officer of business-software company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NOW" class="">ServiceNow</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> said the new New York City law has prompted her to think more about weight as part of the company&#39;s diversity efforts, especially in light of data showing Black and Latina women have a disproportionately high obesity risk.</p><p> ServiceNow&#39;s TruAbility group, which advocates for employees with disabilities, also addresses issues around body size, Pavlin says. She expects other companies will follow with similar employee groups.</p><p> “It&#39;s long overdue,” she said.</p><p> Write to Ray A. Smith at <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>管理</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Diversity</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Career Planning/Management</category><category>歧视</category><category>Physical/Mental Fitness</category><category> Health</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Living/Lifestyle</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Weight Management</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>管理</category><category>labor</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace diversity</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>career planning</category><category>歧视</category><category>physical</category><category> mental fitness</category><category> health</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category>社会问题</category><category>weight management</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Parents Hire $4,000 Sorority Consultants to Help Daughters Dress and Impress During Rush]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Getting into sororities is nearly as tough as entry to top universities; &#39;Be trendy but not too trendy, modest but not too modest, fit in but be unique&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820654/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="去年，Phi Mu 的新成员前往位于阿拉巴马州塔斯卡卢萨的阿拉巴马大学与联谊会姐妹会面。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> New members of Phi Mu en route to meeting with their sorority sisters last year at the University of Alabama in Tuscaloosa, Ala. Will McLelland/USA TODAY NETWORK/Reuters <span>Will McLelland/USA TODAY NETWORK/Reuters</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074760"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074760"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Tara Weiss</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 24, 2023 8:05 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-consultants-rush-colleges-parents-prepare-80b2cfc8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Sorority rush at the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-bulldogs-college-football-playoff-champions-11673323071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">University of Georgia</a> kicks off in August, a lousy time to wear makeup.</p><p> “You need to do it in a way that&#39;s appropriate in southern humidity or else you&#39;re going to have orange rivers running down your face,” said Trisha Addicks. She recommends keeping a “rush bag” with deodorant, portable fan, water and face powder.</p><p> That&#39;s the kind of practical advice Addicks gives clients of her Georgia-based sorority-consulting firm, It&#39;s All Greek to Me. Showing up in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/DOCS" class="company-name">Dr. Martens</a> combat boots, as one client asked about, might not be putting your best foot forward in some <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-house-design-in-the-age-of-instagram-and-rushtok-11672263322?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sorority circles</a> , she said: “During rush, you&#39;re not going to be confident if you&#39;re wearing them, and everybody else is wearing espadrilles.”</p><p> Addicks offers a $600 seminar for women and their mothers to learn the basics about getting into a sorority; $3,500 buys unlimited access to sorority mentors who advise aspirants through every step. She is part of an industry emerging in recent years that sells tips and emotional support to women who want to avoid missteps that threaten first impressions. Sorority consultants cover such topics as what to wear, how to act, what to say and the wisdom of scrubbing potentially off-putting social media posts. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820474?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Shannon Rust, in an outfit curated by her sorority consultant, at the University of Georgia in Athens, Ga., during rush.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Elizabeth Payne</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Emma Kelley, a recent graduate, said hiring Addicks was worth it. Otherwise, she risked entering blind to the arcane rituals, traditions and unspoken rules of Greek life. “You have to be trendy but not too trendy, modest but not too modest, fit in but be unique,” said Kelley, who joined the University of Georgia&#39;s Delta Zeta sorority. The trick, she said, is “blending in and standing out.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820472?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Stacia Damron, founder and CEO of Hiking in Heels.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bridgette Bloomquist Photography</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Getting into sororities has become nearly as competitive as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/youre-about-to-pay-300-000-for-college-whats-another-3-000-in-campus-swag-9a2644eb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">acceptance to top universities.</a> Applicants are asked to write essays, give their grade-point average and report whether they did volunteer work or played high-school sports. Women submit application packets with as many as 30 letters of recommendation, said Stacia Damron, owner of Hiking in High Heels in Texas. Some sororities require that applicants record video responses to their questions. “My boyfriend went to Stanford, and he said this is more complicated than getting a Stanford MBA,” she said.</p><p> Damron tells clients that they need a social-media presence but warns that sorority members will scour a recruit&#39;s posts. She suggests that women erase images of themselves in very skimpy outfits or with alcohol. Instead, they should pile up posts about family, friends, hobbies and volunteer work. “It&#39;s about telling a story to help the sororities get to know you,” said Damron. Her fees run as high as $4,000 for on-call service during rush. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1014" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822501?width=639&amp;height=1014" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sorority consultant Trisha Addicks</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Paige Molina Photography, Atlanta</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Leighton Newberry, owner of Recruitment Ready in Atlanta, said she spends a lot of time prepping young women for conversation. All the hours young people spend texting and communicating over social media has left many inexperienced with face-to-face chitchat, she said. Newberry, who graduated from Auburn University in 2019, advises her clients to make eye contact and stay engaged with new acquaintances during rush season&#39;s many social events. She suggests asking questions: <em>Where are you from? Why did you pick this school to attend?</em></p><p> Newberry has a la carte sessions that cost $150 for video calls and $175 for in-person meetings. She also sells the Bid Day Bundle for $1,000. That includes three one-on-one sessions and assistance writing résumés and cover letters, as well as styling tips. She also gives frank talk about disappointment.</p><p> “You&#39;re not going to get what you want all the time,” Newberry said. “These are life skills that can carry with them for years to come. It&#39;s not just about getting into one sorority.”</p><p> Last year, 125,000 women sought a spot in sororities at the 500 campuses that provide data to the National Panhellenic Conference, and between a quarter and a fifth of them either quit or didn&#39;t get accepted, according to Dani Weatherford, chief executive of the conference, a trade group that represents sororities. Generally, sororities conduct four rounds of meetings with applicants and winnow the group after each round.</p><p> The $2,000 Fabulous and Chic package from Greek Chic in Manhattan provides four sessions on applications, social media and wardrobe, along with &#39;round-the-clock counseling during rush week. Owner Lorie Stefanelli recalled being at a rooftop concert when she got a call from a distraught client at the University of Texas, Austin. The young woman, in tears, had successfully passed several rounds but felt too exhausted to keep going. Stefanelli said she left the concert to soothe her client, telling her she was doing a great job and encouraging her to continue. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820473?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Women lining up for a sorority tour last year at the University of Nebraska in Lincoln, Neb.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Noah Riffe/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Shannon Rust had to bounce back from a few rejections after leaving home in Stamford, Conn., to attend the University of Georgia last year. She had known little about sororities, and her roommate&#39;s mother suggested Addicks, of It&#39;s All Greek to Me. Shannon&#39;s mother, Janine Rust,</p> said she first thought that the idea of paying for a sorority consultant was crazy. But she went ahead and hired Addicks.<p></p><p> Rust said that after Shannon called her to say she had been cut from several sororities, she was more upset than her daughter was. “How could they not want my kid,” Rust recalled thinking. Then she picked up the phone and got consoled by Addicks.</p><p> “Having someone to be able to call 24/7 to talk me off the ledge was immeasurable,” Rust said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 12:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-consultants-rush-colleges-parents-prepare-80b2cfc8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-consultants-rush-colleges-parents-prepare-80b2cfc8<category> a-hed</category><category> Cosmetics/Toiletries</category><category> Skin Care Products</category><category> Footwear</category><category>零售批发</category><category>Clothing Retail</category><category> Specialty Retailing</category><category> Beauty/Personal Care</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Body Care Products</category><category> Clothing/Textiles</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category> Hair Care Products</category><category> Personal Care Products/Appliances</category><category> Personal Care Accessories</category><category>零售</category><category>Specialized Consumer Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学学院</category><category>Selection of Top Stories/Trends/Analysis</category><category> Suggested Reading – Industry News</category><category> Suggested Reading – Accounting/Consulting</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>selection of top stories</category><category> trends</category><category> analysis</category><category> suggested reading – industry news</category><category> suggested reading – accounting</category><category> consulting</category><category> cosmetics</category><category> toiletries</category><category> skin care products</category><category> footwear</category><category>零售</category><category>wholesale</category><category> clothing retail</category><category> specialty retailing</category><category> beauty</category><category> personal care</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>body care products</category><category>衣服</category><category>纺织品</category><category>consumer goods</category><category> hair care products</category><category> personal care products</category><category> appliances</category><category> personal care accessories</category><category> specialized consumer services </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How Workers Really Spend Their Days]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> At the office, we kill time by surreptitiously staring at our phones. Working from home, we make breaks about more than mental distraction. <figure><img src="https://m.wsj.net/video-atmo/20230720/f69a9245-7e28-4d37-912f-3d210afd38e5/1/01wsjanimationlongfin_1000x562.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> TIMO LENZEN FOR THE WALL STREET JOURNAL <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070542"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070542"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-feintzeig"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-736144/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-feintzeig" itemprop="url" rel="author">Rachel Feintzeig</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 23, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Remote-work die-hards like to brag about how they get more work done from home. Truth is, it&#39;s often their downtime that&#39;s so much more productive.</p><p> Kory Black began actually accomplishing things on his breaks when he started working remotely for a credit union last year. Back when he <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-landlord-vornado-bets-1-billion-that-more-commuters-will-return-120ba6e9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">commuted to his job</a> every day, he&#39;d get pulled into <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/working-from-home-has-created-a-hole-that-office-gossip-used-to-fill-11618790400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">office gossip</a> or eat takeout in his car with the sun shade down. Now he pauses his work to give his baby son a bottle, throw in a load of laundry or have a bite in his recliner, the dog on his lap. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1288" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/bfb645e9-77b2-4323-a1f4-31681e946620-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “It&#39;s kind of like you can set your mind off and say, I&#39;m not thinking about work right now,” the 45-year-old South Carolina resident said. “Just breathe in.”</p><p> What do workers do all day? Work, sure. They also <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-working-out-during-the-workday-is-the-ultimate-power-move-11672863482?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">take runs</a> , unload the dishwasher and pop out to the drugstore—if they&#39;re remote. Recent data from Stanford University and other researchers finds that those at home are more likely to exercise, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/women-more-house-work-11632330725?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">complete chores</a> and personal errands, and care for their kids during the workday.</p><p> Employees in the office, meanwhile, are more likely to kill time scrolling the internet or playing a game on their phones, according to the survey of more than 4,500 people.</p><p> When we&#39;re working remotely, our breaks become more precious, ready to be filled with stuff we actually want and need to do. In the office, it&#39;s more about finding that brief mental distraction before plunging into the next task.</p><p> “You can completely shirk at the office,” said Nick Bloom, an economist at Stanford University and one of the authors of the research.</p><p> Workers at home have the option of making more rational choices, Bloom told me. After all, why wait until it&#39;s dark out and places are closed to tackle the rest of your life? Instead, they tap the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-women-can-learn-from-men-about-me-time-787cb114?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">leisure economy</a> during the day, spreading out <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the peak load</a> at hair salons and golf courses.</p><p> “It&#39;s, like, serene and blissful,” he said of rituals like <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-working-out-during-the-workday-is-the-ultimate-power-move-11672863482?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hitting the gym at 11 am</a> . They&#39;ll make up the work tonight—or tomorrow, when they head into the office.</p><h3> Make office breaks better</h3><p> Back in our workplaces, we&#39;re beholden to the cadence of the train schedule and the sense that our colleagues are judging us if we show up late. We feel we can&#39;t openly chip away at our personal to-do lists, so we turn our laptop screens or click back to our email when the boss strolls over.</p><p> Still, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-to-escape-your-packed-schedule-and-take-a-rest-from-work-11667749139?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">we need breaks</a> .</p><p> “Our expectation as a whole that people are never going to tend their personal lives while they&#39;re at work is absolutely ridiculous,” said Pam Sampson, who leads a staff of 800 as the chief program officer of a Massachusetts nonprofit.</p><p> Nearly all her staff work in-person five days a week. She knows they log on to Amazon for Prime Day, or pause to call their doctor&#39;s office for an appointment. She worries, though, that, left to their own devices, they&#39;ll “work and work and work and they&#39;ll become crabbier and crabbier and crabbier,” she said.</p><p> Hence, a mandated break that Sampson has coined, “Pam&#39;s Stupid Games.” Every six weeks or so, she&#39;ll convene 50 of her managers for a daytime scavenger hunt across central Massachusetts or an afternoon in an escape room.</p><p> “I force people to do something,” she said.</p><h3> Good distractions</h3><p> On-site workers clock 12 more minutes of productivity a day on average, according to an analysis of 91,000 employees by ActivTrak, a maker of workforce analytics software. They do take breaks—two more a week than remote workers, according to ActivTrak. Those breaks are shorter than their counterparts&#39; at home, who often contend with distractions from partners, kids, even <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/seasonal-hazard-for-working-at-home-leaf-blowers-11603210825?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">leafblowers</a> . Office workers&#39; focus sessions—time when they&#39;re not multitasking, or away from their computers—are also more frequent.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Are you more productive working in the office or from home?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Gabriela Mauch, vice president of ActivTrak&#39;s productivity lab, suspects that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/was-the-office-always-this-distracting-get-ruthless-about-your-productivity-now-11635739260?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">disruptions at the office</a> , like responding to a colleague&#39;s question, are more likely to prompt workers to dive back into their tasks quicker. Such distractions could even set one down a better path with a project, in a way that mopping your kitchen floors is unlikely to do.</p><p> “The presence of other people gets us to be better people,” said Ayelet Fishbach, a professor of behavioral science and marketing at University of Chicago&#39;s Booth School of Business and the author of a book about harnessing motivation. We absorb others&#39; schedules via osmosis, she adds, and fall into natural breaks somewhere between work and play, like grabbing coffee with a co-worker.</p><p> Alone at home, “you constantly have a fear of like, What are you missing? What is the opportunity cost? What should I have been doing?”她说。</p><h3> &#39;Breaks I choose to take&#39;</h3><p> Many employers would surely agree that breaks at the office are more productive. But most of the hybrid and remote workers I spoke to are clinging to the freedom of working at home. They say they log on from their kitchen tables early, before their inboxes are swamped with requests, and find they can get tasks done in half the time. They plop their babies in office playpens, pop casseroles in the oven, set timers on their watches and relish control of their time.</p><p> “The breaks at home are the breaks I choose to take,” Larry Lock, a 26-year-old hybrid worker in Virginia, told me. “And the breaks in the office are the ones that are taken for me.”</p><p> Brenda Schumacher, a marketing and communications professional in the Dallas area, remembers walking into her office complex every day at 9 am to face the long warm-up: colleagues exchanging hellos, putting away their lunches, filling up coffee cups.</p><p> “Nothing really got done that first hour,” she said. “That was our work-life balance, right there.”</p><p> Same thing at the end of the day, as people wound down, she said. If she wrapped her work early, she felt unable to leave even though the job was done.</p><p> Starting a remote job last year, she found the idea of working, and breaking, on her own time thrilling.</p><p> “You don&#39;t have to go up to everyone and go, &#39;How was your weekend?&#39; ” she said. “You can just get to work.”</p><p> Write to Rachel Feintzeig at <a href="mailto:Rachel.Feintzeig@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Rachel.Feintzeig@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/abc0d988-98a3-49dd-87e2-f6d4256e8c3e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f<author><![CDATA[Rachel Feintzeig]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Work-Life Balance</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Career Planning/Management</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Telecommuting</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> work-life balance</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>career planning</category><category>管理</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category> telecommuting</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Road to Surrender’ Review: The Coming of the A-Bomb]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> 1945 年 8 月 6 日，美国投下了第一颗原子弹。又过了一年，我们才完全了解发生了什么。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093990421082502"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822330?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">哈里·杜鲁门总统和战争部长亨利·史汀生讨论对日本的原子弹爆炸。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贝特曼档案</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093990421082502"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-auslin" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·奥斯林</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 23 日下午 4:12 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/road-to-surrender-review-the-coming-of-the-a-bomb-25cc9174"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>与 1945 年 8 月 6 日原子弹投下时立即摧毁广岛的物理冲击波不同，原子弹的精神冲击波花了一年多的时间才袭击美国。 1946 年 8 月，约翰·赫西 (John Hersey) 发表了对这一事件的尖锐描述——占据了《纽约客》整期的篇幅。此后，美国人开始就原子弹问题展开争论，从未停止过。日本的原子弹爆炸合理吗？如果没有他们，战争会结束吗？这次袭击是否像吓唬日本人一样吓唬苏联人？正如克里斯托弗·诺兰的电影《奥本海默》所展示的那样，冲击波仍在回响。</p><p>资深传记作家埃文·托马斯现在加入了辩论。在《投降之路》中，托马斯先生描绘了直接参与投掷炸弹和结束太平洋战争决定的三名男子的心态和情感：战争部长亨利·史汀生、日本外务大臣东乡茂德和陆军空军上将卡尔·“图伊”·斯帕茨。其他关键人物也很突出，特别是哈里·杜鲁门总统、乔治·马歇尔将军、陆军中将莱斯利·格罗夫斯和前面提到的监督该武器建造的物理学家 J·罗伯特·奥本海默。</p><p>这些人所承受的沉重的心理压力构成了本书的道德戏剧。托马斯先生特别擅长描绘他们在努力解决时机、目标、和平条件和国内政治问题时所面临的不确定性，展示了每项决定是如何经过辩论和痛苦的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/0f9e421a-55c4-46a6-9d90-a25fd2238feb.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>然而，如果美国人有一个确定性的话，那就是炸弹一旦投入使用就会被使用。正如史汀生在 1947 年发表在《哈泼斯》杂志上的决定辩护中所言，“我看不出像我这样肩负如此责任的人会采取任何其他做法”，而不是建议投下原子弹。托马斯先生展示了史汀生和他的同事如何努力解决用可怕的新武器瞄准平民的困境，他们说服自己广岛和长崎主要是军事场所，但实际上它们并不是。</p><p>原子弹的历史已经被广泛报道，但托马斯先生轻快的叙述却让读者陷入了困扰日本和美国政策制定者的道德困境。对东乡的关注以及日本最高战争委员会的曲折僵局揭示了一个比大多数美国人所熟悉的故事复杂得多的故事：长崎被消灭后日本迅速投降。东京的诸神黄昏与 1945 年初在柏林的诸神黄昏类似。托马斯先生明确表示，即使在裕仁天皇明确表示希望战争结束之后，投降的决定也是一场势均力敌的事情。</p><p>同样引人注目，而且对许多读者来说可能是新鲜的，是美国在民用与军事控制新武器方面的短暂但至关重要的斗争。最初，军方拥有唯一的权力。第三枚炸弹于 1945 年夏天准备就绪，最有可能在 8 月底或 9 月在东京使用。在收到对广岛和长崎造成的破坏的完整描述，包括平民死亡人数的说明后，杜鲁门总统下令只有在他的明确命令下才能使用更多的原子弹——这是美国历史上第一次由总统直接控制军事武器。近80年后，总统对核武器的唯一控制权问题再次成为热门话题，美国新任总统的智力受到两党人士的质疑。</p><p>原子弹爆炸的最大争议之一是它们是否像针对东京一样针对莫斯科。托马斯先生简要介绍了修正主义的论点，即该炸弹被不道德地用于针对平民，以便让华盛顿在即将出现的冷战中占据一席之地。正如托马斯先生所表明的那样，地缘政治是一个因素，但远非杜鲁门和史汀生思想中的主要因素。</p><p>同样令史汀生烦恼且至关重要的是国家与国际对原子能的控制问题。美国对保持对原子能的唯一控制有着强烈的兴趣。然而与此同时，其他国家，尤其是苏联，最终肯定会获得这项技术。史汀生等人认为，最好从一开始就建立一个国际治理体系。因此，防扩散问题，就像民用控制原子弹的问题一样，是在原子时代初期诞生的。史汀生的梦想注定只能是这样。</p><p>至于投下这两颗炸弹的必要性，托马斯先生和大多数历史学家一样，对此毫无疑问。计划于 1945 年 11 月开始入侵日本本土，美军预计伤亡人数将达到数十万人，更不用说预计将有数百万日本人丧生，其中包括平民。即使在广岛事件之后，裕仁天皇的大臣们也无法同意投降。只有在长崎和苏联于 8 月 7 日（广岛核事故发生后的第二天）对日本宣战之后，东乡才能让战争委员会的多数成员（尽管不是军事领导人）承受难以忍受的痛苦。</p><p>杜鲁门和他的顾问最初认为原子弹虽然威力独特，但会像任何其他武器一样使用。然而，在广岛事件之后，他们了解了它的革命本质，道格拉斯·麦克阿瑟将军等高级军事领导人认识到它永远改变了战争。</p><p>他们也不能忽视道德问题是双向的。在爆炸中丧生的数十万日本人中，双方都有无数人获救，其中包括托马斯先生的父亲，他是一名正在等待入侵日本命令的美国海军初级军官。</p><p><em>奥斯林先生是斯坦福大学胡佛研究所的历史学家，最近着有《亚洲新地缘政治》一书。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 20:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/road-to-surrender-review-the-coming-of-the-a-bomb-25cc9174</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/road-to-surrender-review-the-coming-of-the-a-bomb-25cc9174<author><![CDATA[Michael Auslin]]></author><category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Arts Calendar: Happenings for the Week of July 23]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> &#39;Futurama&#39; and Joni Mitchell make eagerly awaited returns, Disney&#39;s &#39;Haunted Mansion&#39; adds some spookiness to the summer, Jason Alexander makes his debut as a Broadway director and more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022748"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821131?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A scene from &#39;Futurama&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: HULU</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022748"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> WSJ Arts in Review Staff</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 23, 2023 5:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-23-airdigital-c2ab4e82"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><h3> Film</h3><p> • <strong>“Haunted Mansion”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : While we&#39;re still months out from spooky season, Disney is hoping to get in on the light-fright fest early with this adaptation of its popular ride. LaKeith Stanfield, Tiffany Haddish, Owen Wilson, Danny DeVito, Rosario Dawson, Jamie Lee Curtis and Winona Ryder are among the creepy cast in this tried-and-true horror setup, directed by Justin Simien, of a family that moves into a house to find it already occupied by supernatural tenants.</p><p> • <strong>“Talk to Me”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : Scarier than any Disney fare is the debut from brothers Danny and Michael Philippou about a group that dives into occult conjurings with the help of an embalmed hand. One assumes the oddities shop was out of monkey paws.</p><p> • <strong>“The First Slam Dunk”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : Takehiko Inoue directs this anime film based on his own manga about dueling high-school basketball teams.</p><p> • <strong>“The Beasts”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : Highly decorated at this year&#39;s Goya Awards (the Oscars of Spain), the new film from Rodrigo Sorogoyen (“The Realm”) tells the story—based on actual events—of escalating tensions between a French couple and their neighbors in the Galician countryside.</p><p> • <strong>“Sympathy for the Devil”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : Yuval Adler, whose “Bethlehem” won the Ophir Award (this one the Oscars of Israel), directs a thriller in which a driver ( Joel Kinnaman ) is forced to play chauffeur to a mysterious man ( Nicolas Cage ) who is holding him at gunpoint.</p><p> • <strong>“War Pony”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : After winning praise at Cannes and strong reviews in the UK, where it was released last month, Riley Keough and Gina Gammell&#39;s portrait of two Lakota boys on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation makes its way to American screens.</p><h3> TV</h3><p> • <strong>“Special Ops: Lioness”</strong> <em>(Paramount+, July 23)</em> : Taylor Sheridan seems happy to work on either side of the camera, whether winning fans and enemies in his roles on “Sons of Anarchy” and “Veronica Mars,” winning critical acclaim for films like “Sicario” and “Hell or High Water,” or winning eyeballs with sleeper hit series like “Yellowstone” and its rustic offspring. He&#39;s back in the creator&#39;s seat with a new spy thriller that stars Zoe Saldaña as a CIA chief guiding a young woman in infiltrating a terrorist organization. Nicole Kidman, Morgan Freeman and Michael Kelly are also among the familiar faces in the covert drama.</p><p> • <strong>“Son of a Critch”</strong> <em>(The CW, July 24)</em> : A series based on the memoir of comedian Mark Critch brings his awkward middle-school childhood in 1980s Newfoundland to life. Our critic <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/son-of-a-critch-review-a-comics-chaotic-coming-of-age-abb4ea14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">compares it to</a> “&#39;The Wonder Years&#39; if it were written by Jean Shepherd, with additional dialogue by Judy Blume and Hunter S. Thompson. ”</p><p> • <strong>“The Golden Boy”</strong> <em>(HBO, July 24)</em> : The multi-time world champ Oscar De La Hoya didn&#39;t get his nickname, which lends the title to Fernando Villena&#39;s</p> documentary about the boxer, from being a Golden Gloves winner. It came from his mission, eventually fulfilled, to grant his mother&#39;s wish that he win at the Olympics. She didn&#39;t live to see that achievement, but Mr. Villena&#39;s profile goes into the fighter&#39;s quest and more over its two episodes.<p></p><p> • <strong>“Futurama”</strong> <em>(Hulu, July 24)</em> : Good news everyone! A decade after disappearing into a black hole, the Matt Groening animated comedy is back—and with its full original cast intact, even if the Planet Express ship has seen better days.</p><p> • <strong>“Happiness for Beginners”</strong> <em>(Netflix, July 27)</em> : Katherine Center&#39;s hit novel about a romance that blossoms during a hike on the Appalachian Trail gets a screen adaptation from Vicky Wight, who also directs. Ellie Kemper and Luke Grimes lead as the star-crossed trekkers.</p><p> • <strong>“Twisted Metal”</strong> <em>(Peacock, July 27)</em> : Thanks to shows like “The Witcher” and “The Last of Us,” video games have proved to have success beyond the console. Now, the PlayStation classic—a demolition-derby-based relic from the &#39;90s—starts its lethal engine with Anthony Mackie playing a delivery driver looking to evade chaos on his way to a better life.</p><p> • <strong>“Zoey 102”</strong> <em>(Paramount+, July 27)</em> : “Zoey 101” was a tween hit in the aughts, with its story of a girl changing the norm at a formerly all-boys school. Now Zoey is all grown up—but still played by</p> Jamie Lynn Spears —and attending her former classmates&#39; tropical wedding in a new film.<p></p><p> • <strong>“Captain Fall”</strong> <em>(Netflix, July 28)</em> : After being hired to skipper a swanky cruiseliner, a captain discovers that it&#39;s a front for a bigtime smuggling ring. Jason Ritter, Christopher Meloni and Lesley-Ann Brandt crew the sea-bound animated comedy.</p><p> • <strong>“Good Omens,” season 2</strong> <em>(Prime Video, July 28</em> ): Michael Sheen and David Tennant return from heaven and hell for a second season of the show (four years after it premiered), inspired by the Terry Pratchett – Neil Gaiman novel, about good-natured interlopers from beyond the earthly plane who have set aside their differences to maintain a peaceful existence in the here-and-now.</p><p> • <strong>“Hidden Strike”</strong> <em>(Netflix, July 28)</em> : Scott Waugh directs this action-comedy about two ex-special forces members ( John Cena and Jackie Chan ) tasked with leading civilians to safety through Iraq&#39;s notorious “Highway of Death.”</p><h3> Theater</h3><p> • <strong>“The Cottage”</strong> <em>(Hayes Theater, New York, opens July 24)</em> : Jason Alexander might be best known for his on-screen work in “Seinfeld,” but he&#39;s also a familiar face in the theater world, having won a Tony for his performance in “ Jerome Robbins &#39; Broadway.” Now he makes his Broadway directorial debut helming Sandy Rustin&#39;s new romantic comedy about a woman who reveals her affair to her husband and her lover&#39;s spouse. Eric McCormack, Laura Bell Bundy, Lilli Cooper, Nehal Joshi, Alex Moffat and Dana Steingold</p> star.<p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821134?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Joni Mitchell performing at the 2022 Newport Folk Festival</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Douglas Mason/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>音乐</h3><p>• <strong>Beverly Glenn-Copeland, “The Ones Ahead”</strong> <em>(July 28th)</em> : The Canadian new-age/folk/electronic musician, whose 1986 “Keyboard Fantasies” only recently found widespread popularity, releases his first new studio album in almost 20 years: a hopeful, forward-looking record that deeply believes in the power of song.</p><p> • <strong>Joni Mitchell, “Joni Mitchell at Newport”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : Last summer, the storied Newport Folk Festival finally returned to its usual format after Covid-19 had derailed it. An especially welcome aspect of its re-emergence was a surprise set by folk legend Joni Mitchell, her first full-length performance in some two decades. For those who weren&#39;t in Rhode Island that day, a recording of the concert, which featured Brandi Carlile among an impressive roster of other talent, is now being made available.</p><p> • <strong>Post Malone, “Austin”</strong> <em>(July 28)</em> : The rapper-singer issues his fifth studio album, which draws its title from his birth name and hints at a more personal direction in his music.</p><h3> Opera</h3><p> • <strong>“Orfeo”</strong> <em>(Crosby Theatre, Santa Fe, NM, July 29-Aug. 24)</em> : Santa Fe Opera presents Claudio Monteverdi&#39;s opera of the classic love story between Orfeo and Euridice in a new production by Yuval Sharon with never-before-heard orchestration from Nico Muhly.</p><h3>艺术</h3><p>• <strong>“Columbia MFA”</strong> <em>(Storage, New York, July 28-Aug. 25)</em> : If MFA programs provide a launching pad for young artists, exhibitions of their work are the rocket fuel that helps their careers take off. A selection of creations from more than 20 artists in Columbia&#39;s prestigious program will be on view at this artist-run space in Tribeca.</p><h3> Last Call</h3><p> • <strong>“Horses: The Death of a Rider”</strong> <em>(Vito Schnabel, New York, closes July 28)</em> : This intimate gallery show presents 16 paintings by the Italian artist Giorgio de Chirico, best known for his metaphysical and surrealist work, that focus on the importance of equines throughout his career. Spanning nearly a half-century, his paintings of horses connect with his broader oeuvre by embracing classical imagery while slyly upending it.</p><p> For additional Arts Calendar listings visit wsj.com. Write to brian.kelly@wsj.com and julia.fischer@wsj.com.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-23-airdigital-c2ab4e82</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-23-airdigital-c2ab4e82<category> arts in review</category><category>管理</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category>电影</category><category>音乐</category><category>Theater</category><category> Television/Radio</category><category> Calendar of Events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>管理</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category>电影</category><category>music</category><category> theater</category><category> television</category><category> radio</category><category> calendar of events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Black Orpheus: Jacob Lawrence and the Mbari Club’ Review: Global Origins]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> An exhibition at the Toledo Museum of Art highlights the African-American painter&#39;s trips to Nigeria and the influence of the vibrant postcolonial community he found there, displaying his paintings alongside art by his contemporaries from around the world. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590084301765015366"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="611" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821686?width=860&amp;height=611" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Market Scene&#39; (1966) by Jacob Lawrence</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Jacob and Gwendolyn Knight Lawrence Foundation/ARS, NY </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590084301765015366"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Lance Esplund</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 22, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-orpheus-jacob-lawrence-and-the-mbari-club-review-global-origins-f5ea375"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Toledo, Ohio</em></p><p> Jacob Lawrence (1917-2000), who painted the African-American experience, is among the most well-known and respected black American figurative artists of the 20th century. But a new exhibition, “Black Orpheus: Jacob Lawrence and the Mbari Club” (at Ohio&#39;s Toledo Museum of Art through Sept. 3), puts Lawrence on the international stage, as it broadens our understanding of the artist, his influences and his art. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Black Orpheus: Jacob Lawrence and the Mbari Club</strong></p><p> <em>Toledo Museum of Art, through Sept. 3, 2023</em></p></div></div><p> Born in Atlantic City, NJ, Lawrence lived in Philadelphia and then in Harlem, where he began studying art at 13 years old. Although he dropped out of school at 16, Lawrence would later teach art at Black Mountain College, the New School for Social Research and Pratt Institute. The traditional account of Lawrence&#39;s career, and of his semi-abstract paintings—dynamic interplays of brightly colored and dark patches of tempera and gouache—highlights the influences of the Harlem Renaissance, jazz and European modernism, especially Picasso&#39;s Cubism and Matisse&#39;s abstract cutouts.</p><p> Usually, we see Lawrence exhibited by himself or among contemporaneous American artists. His celebrated narratives include painting series devoted to the early turbulent decades of American history; the lives of Harriet Tubman, Frederick Douglass and John Brown ; the Great Migration of African-Americans who (like Lawrence&#39;s parents) fled the Jim Crow South for the urban North; his stint in the US Coast Guard during World War II; and the bombing of Hiroshima. In these multicultural artworks, Lawrence, though not colorblind, emphasizes the integration of races and the universal aspects of a shared American history. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821865?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Installation view</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Toledo Museum of Art</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But “Black Orpheus” demonstrates that this version of Lawrence&#39;s life and art is at best incomplete. Co-organized by the Chrysler Museum of Art and the New Orleans Museum of Art, “Black Orpheus” focuses on two transformative, inspirational trips Lawrence took to Nigeria (for 10 days in 1962; and, with his wife, the artist Gwendolyn Knight, for eight months in 1964). In Africa, Lawrence showed paintings from his “Migration” and “War” series in global exhibitions of the Mbari Club—an experimental, international collective of artists, writers and performers who embraced European modernism and indigenous African culture (“mbari” is an Igbo word for creation). Lawrence saw art performances, attended workshops and painted Africans&#39; daily life. In 1963, he was featured in Black Orpheus, the Mbari Club&#39;s journal of art and literature.</p><p> Co-curated by Kimberli Gant, at the Brooklyn Museum and formerly at the Chrysler, and Ndubuisi Ezeluomba, at the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts and formerly at NOMA, “Black Orpheus” is an illuminating time capsule. It includes more than 100 objects by artists from Nigeria, Ghana, Ethiopia, Sudan, Brazil, India, Japan, England, Europe and the US Fascinating and diverse, it deepens our experience of Lawrence and his synthesis of Western and African heritages in postcolonial Africa&#39;s increasingly global community. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="642" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821687?width=860&amp;height=642" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Four Sheep&#39; (1964) by Jacob Lawrence</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Jacob and Gwendolyn Knight Lawrence Foundation/ARS, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This melting-pot atmosphere, with mixed results, inspired a range of hybrid art. Lawrence benefited immediately. His African paintings (mostly market scenes) feel jump-started—more abstract, colorful, hieratic, rhythmic and alive. In “Clown” (1963), Lawrence deconstructs the performer into a totemic arrangement of hat, head, hands and flowers. In “Four Sheep” (1964), vignettes of women—tending children, cleaning fish, dressing meat and preparing meals—swirl as if in a vortex around a central still life of sheep skulls. Bloody crimson carcasses in “Meat Market” and “Roosters” (both 1964) give village life the visceral impact of a depiction of the Last Judgment. In these and other crowded, energetic paintings, Lawrence compartmentalizes and stacks scenes, treating his compositions as if they were African relief sculptures or, as in “Antiquities” (1964)—depicting a woman and religious figurines—dreamlike visions. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="623" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821691?width=700&amp;height=623" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;New England Forest in Winter&#39; (1967) by Naoko Matsubara</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Philadelphia Museum of Art/Toledo Museum of Art</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Lawrence, though featured, doesn&#39;t steal the show. Included here are woodcuts by the German expressionist Karl Schmidt-Rottluff and fantastical, abstract cosmic landscapes and a seemingly Modigliani-inspired portrait by the pioneering Ethiopian modernist Alexander “Skunder” Boghossian. Paintings on plywood by Nigerian painter Twins Seven-Seven suggest intricate textiles. Japanese artist Naoko Matsubara&#39;s woodcut “New England Forest in Winter” (1967) is both visceral and delicate; and Austrian artist Susanne Wenger&#39;s textiles and sculptural reliefs are graphic and striking. Nigerian Chief Muraina Oyelami&#39;s painting, “Untitled (Noble Man)” (1965), though reminiscent of Paul Klee, is genuine—satisfyingly other. And Ahmed Mohammed Shibrain&#39;s “Untitled” (1963) flits among traditional calligraphy, graffiti and ink drawings by the American sculptor David Smith. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="853" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821689?width=700&amp;height=853" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Untitled&#39; (1966) by Alexander &#39;Skunder&#39; Boghossian</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Chrysler Museum of Art/Toledo Museum of Art</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Most impressive, however, are the exhibition&#39;s sculptures. Brazilian artist Agnaldo dos Santos&#39;s sleek, carved-wood neck and head, “Exu” (c. 1950s), is as forceful as a clenched fist. The large, undated, abstract aluminum reliefs in counter-repoussé—“Untitled (Adam and Eve),” “Untitled (History of Oshogbo)” and “Untitled (The King and His Followers)”—by Nigerian artist Asiru Olatunde meld African, Assyrian and folk-art traditions. They are stunning. Spectacular, also, is the steel sculpture of a reclining, allegorical female figure, “Awakening Africa” (c. 1959-60), by Ghanaian sculptor Vincent Kofi.</p> Though straining upward, she is regal, monumental.<p></p><p> To its credit, “Black Orpheus” doesn&#39;t push any major theses. Though erring in presentation toward the theatrical, this enriching, informative show reframes and recontextualizes Lawrence. Underscoring the African heritage of an African-American artist, “Black Orpheus” allows us to see its artworks in dialogue, to make visual connections among its many voices and to experience Lawrence afresh.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Esplund, the author of “The Art of Looking: How to Read Modern and Contemporary Art” (Basic Books), writes about art for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-orpheus-jacob-lawrence-and-the-mbari-club-review-global-origins-f5ea375</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/article